Description. Body (
Figs. 1–2
) slender, broadened posteriorly; dorsal surface almost completely covered with dense and erect setae.

Head. Head capsule (
Figs. 3–5
) approximately circular, gently convex dorsally. Eyes (
Figs. 3–5
) oval in lateral view, somewhat prominent. Infraorbital carina absent (
Fig. 5
). Antennae (
Figs. 1–5
) 11 -segmented, moniliform, almost as long as head and pronotum combined.

Mouthparts. Labrum (
Fig. 6
) strongly transverse (width/length ratio 2.1 ), rounded anteriorly; surface covered with some 45–50 pseudopores, except for posterior and lateral areas; apodeme roundly produced posteromedially, with lateral arm gently curved and its apex hidden under postero-medial projection of apodeme. Epipharynx as in
Fig. 7
. with long sensilla a , its medial sensory field with 11 pores and numerous minute sensory pseudopores; lateral row with 3–5 pores distributed between membranous wrinkles; 3 marginal setae slender, about 10 times as long as wide. Mandibles (
Figs. 8–10
) slightly asymmetric, mesal areas of dorsal surface covered with 30–40 pseudopores; prostheca obtuse at apex, its inner margin densely spinulate; left mandible (
Figs. 8–9
) generalised, without teeth; 3 small setae present laterally; right mandible (
Fig. 10
) with a small tooth at middle of inner margin, weakly serrate between tooth and apex; 3 small setae present laterally. Labium as in
Figs. 11–12
. Prementum (
Fig. 11
) with 2 real pores and 1 setal pore latero-mesally, 3–5 pseudopores between real pores, and 25–30 medial pseudopores; internal ridge (
Fig. 11
; indicated with arrow) very small, its length less than 1 / 6 that of prementum; apodeme (
Fig. 11
) with broom-like projections posteromedially, lateral lobe of apodeme (
Fig. 11
) gently curved, narrowed apically, pointed at apex. Ligula (
Fig. 11
) bilobed, with each lobe rounded and covered with minute pores apically; apical setae absent; lateral margin weakly sclerotized. Labial palpus (
Figs. 11
) with segment I long and twice as long as II; segment II notched from base to apex forming membranous zone, which bears one pore; segment III longer than II, slightly dilated apically, with 1 pore near apex, covered with spinulae at apex; setae α, β, and γ present. Hypopharynx (
Fig. 12
) generalised, without apical seta; medial sensory field simplified, with small ridges. Maxilla as in
Figs. 13–17
. Cardo (
Fig. 13
) generalised, almost elliptical in ventral view, with about 10 pseudopores. Stipes (
Fig. 13
) small, triangular, with 3 setae around base, and 5 or 6 pseudopores. Palpifer (
Fig. 13
) triangular in lateral view, with one large seta near apex, two small setae at middle and apex, and with some 5 pseudopores. Lacinia (
Figs. 13–15
) with some 6–8 pores around base and 2 setae laterally; apical inner margin with a row of 8 spines forming comb; surface around comb densely pubescent, and with a row of pores. Subgalea (
Fig. 13
) weakly sclerotized. Galea (
Figs. 13, 16– 17
) broad, about 2.5 times as long as wide, slightly curved at middle, gently narrowed apically, with about 10 pores around middle of outer margin, densely pubescent and with pampas grass-like projection apically. Maxillary palpus as in
Fig. 13
; segment I very small, without setae; segment II gently curved, and much dilated apically, with some pores along apical margin; segment III largest, 1.5 times longer than 2 nd, almost straight, widest at middle, moderately covered with pores except for basal and apical margins; 4 th long, narrowed apically, with one pore around middle. Mentum (
Fig. 18
) trapeziform; anterior margin with a pair of projections, which bear seta u ; posterior margin completely truncate; surface moderately covered with pseudopores except for antero-lateral area; seta w located antero-mesally.

Thorax . Pronotum ( Figs. 1 , 19 ) slightly transverse, angles widely rounded; microsetae directed anteriad in midline; in lateral portions of disk microsetae directed laterad ( Type I,
Benick & Lohse 1974
). Hypomera (
Fig. 19
) visible laterally. Prosternum (
Fig. 20
) transversely sutured; densely covered with setae along anterior margin; posterior margin truncate. Scutellum generalised, its apex acutely pointed ( Figs. 1 , 22 ). Mesoventrite (
Fig. 21
) with mesoventral process moderate in length, 0.6 times as long as coxal cavities. Mesocoxae are moderately separated. Mesocoxal cavity not margined (
Fig. 21
). Hind wing reduced, and about as long as elytron.

Legs . Tarsal formula 4-5 - 5 . Medial macroseta of mesotibia thin, slightly longer than tibial width. Empodium (
Fig. 23
) simple, without setae.

Abdomen. Segments III–VII (
Fig. 1
) with posterior margin almost straight; surface densely covered with erect setae. Tergites III–V with moderate basal impressions. Abdominal tergite VIII (
Fig. 24
) with basal suture curved laterally and continued apicad; sternite (
Fig. 25
) with basal suture reaching lateral sides. Tergites IX and X densely covered with setae.

Male characters . Sternite VIII (
Figs. 25–26
) with apical margin weakly sclerotized forming transparent zone, lacking minute pubescence and with apical sensory setae which are 1.5 times as long as in female. Aedeagus: median lobe (
Figs. 28–29
) with basal capsule bulbous; distal crests fused on their sides, projecting; copulatory piece ( Figs. 30, 31 ) bent in lateral view; paramere (
Figs. 32–33
) with condylite almost straight; hinge zone obscure.

Female characters . Sternite VIII (
Fig. 27
) with apical margin fully sclerotized, with minute pubescence and apical sensory setae shorter than in male. Spermatheca (
Figs. 34–35
) with capsule much shorter than elongate stem.
